I'd like to be able to create versionless links to the documentation, for use in error messages, code comments, etc. For example, a message like `see https://click.palletsprojects.com/windows for more information`. I don't want to use URLs with versions because I would have to remember to modify all instances of it before releasing a new version.

Currently, only the root path redirects to the default version, other paths raise a 404. Instead, the path should be preserved and appended to the default version path on redirect.

```
Works:
https://click.palletsprojects.com/ -> https://click.palletsprojects.com/en/7.x/

Doesn't work, 404:
https://click.palletsprojects.com/windows -> https://click.palletsprojects.com/en/7.x/windows
```

I do not want to use the "latest" or "stable" versions because I would like the URLs that people land on and share to contain the actual version.

I already do this with the transitional redirects I set up from `click.pocoo.org` to `click.palletsprojects.com`. A similar approach could probably be used to extend RTD's default redirect.

```nginx
location ~ ^/dev(.*)$ {
  return 301 https://click.palletsprojects.com/en/master$1;
}

location ~ ^/(\d)(.*)$ {
  return 301 https://click.palletsprojects.com/en/$1.x$2;
}

location ~ ^/latest(.*)$ {
  return 301 https://click.palletsprojects.com/en/7.x$1;
}

location / {
  return 301 https://click.palletsprojects.com/en/7.x$request_uri;
}
```

## Details

* Project URL: 
     - Readthedocs link: http://dedupe.readthedocs.io
     - Custom domain: https://dedupe.io/developers/library
* Docs repo on GitHub: https://github.com/dedupeio/dedupe/tree/master/docs

## Expected Result

Docs should load at the custom domain (https://dedupe.io/developers/library) and use custom styles:

![dedupe-theme](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/14170650/36343977-34ea8ffc-13d9-11e8-8308-4d6202eecdf7.png)

These styles are simple tweaks on top of the default `sphinx_rtd_theme`, which are defined in a static CSS file that gets loaded in the layout template. Custom CSS [here](https://github.com/dedupeio/dedupe/blob/master/docs/_static/css/custom.css); custom layout [here](https://github.com/dedupeio/dedupe/blob/master/docs/_templates/layout.html).

## Actual Result

Intermittently, https://dedupe.io/developers/library returns the readthedocs 404 page:

![readthedocs-404](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/634572/36285151-4daafb4c-125f-11e8-925e-267574cc941f.png)

Sometimes the custom styles fail to load:

![weird-styles](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/634572/36285152-4dc27628-125f-11e8-881e-d9b1bede6e03.png)

~In the case of the missing styles, the stylesheet still seems to be available from https://dedupe.io/developers/library/en/latest/_static/css/custom.css and is visible in the Resources tab in the dev tools, but the styles aren't applied to the page.~ During response periods where the styles seem wonky, the correponding stylesheets also 404. (See more in [my comment below](https://github.com/rtfd/readthedocs.org/issues/3630#issuecomment-366461120).) This makes me think that the 404s are the root of the issue.

In both cases, hard refreshing a few times appears to fix the issue, but then the behavior recurs sporadically.

Some other interesting behavior:

- I've tested this in Firefox 60.0a1(nightly build) and Chrome 63.0.3239.132, both on Ubuntu 16.04. The behavior happens sporadically in both browsers, although it seems more frequent on Chrome.
- I can't replicate either issue locally, or on the readthedocs subdomain (http://dedupe.readthedocs.io). This makes me think that something is up with the custom domain.

Here are the Nginx rules we use for proxying the custom domain:

```nginx
    location /developers/library/ {
        proxy_pass https://dedupe.readthedocs.io/;
        proxy_set_header Host $http_host;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto https;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Scheme $scheme;
        proxy_set_header X-RTD-SLUG dedupe;
        proxy_connect_timeout 10s;
        proxy_read_timeout 20s;
    }

    location /developers/library/index.html {
        return 301 https://dedupe.io/developers/library/;
    }

    location /en {
        return 301 https://dedupe.io/developers/library$uri;
    }
```

Any thoughts on how I can debug further would be appreciated!

GitHub used to return a 201 response on a duplicate webhook, but now returns a `422` response. Existing logic expects GitHub to handle overwrite, but we need to handle this on our end instead.

Error response on failure:

```
